{"award_age":38.0,"bio_image":"full\/961f78f2401ba7de26d69d84a37c6bef262d96b6.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1916-08-25T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"2003-08-04T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/en\/thumb\/4\/45\/Frederick_Chapman_Robbins_nobel.jpg\/220px-Frederick_Chapman_Robbins_nobel.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Frederick_C._Robbins","mini_bio":"<p><b>Frederick Chapman Robbins<\/b> (August 25, 1916 \u2013 August 4, 2003) was an American pediatrician and virologist.<\/p><p>He received the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> in 1954 along with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Franklin_Enders\" title=\"John Franklin Enders\">John Franklin Enders<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Thomas_Huckle_Weller\" title=\"Thomas Huckle Weller\">Thomas Huckle Weller<\/a>, making Robbins the only Nobel laureate born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Alabama\" title=\"Alabama\">Alabama<\/a>. The award was for his breakthrough work in isolation and growth of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Polio\" title=\"Polio\" class=\"mw-redirect\">polio<\/a> virus, paving the way for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Vaccines\" title=\"Vaccines\" class=\"mw-redirect\">vaccines<\/a> developed by <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Jonas_Salk\" title=\"Jonas Salk\">Jonas Salk<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Albert_Sabin\" title=\"Albert Sabin\">Albert Sabin<\/a>, etc. He attended school at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Missouri\" title=\"University of Missouri\">University of Missouri<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Harvard_University\" title=\"Harvard University\">Harvard University<\/a>.<\/p><p>In 1952, he was appointed as Professor of Pediatrics at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Case_Western_Reserve_University_School_of_Medicine\" title=\"Case Western Reserve University School of Medicine\">Case Western Reserve University<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Frederick_C._Robbins#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Robbins was elected a Fellow of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/American_Academy_of_Arts_and_Sciences\" title=\"American Academy of Arts and Sciences\">American Academy of Arts and Sciences<\/a> in 1962.<sup id=\"cite_ref-AAAS_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Frederick_C._Robbins#cite_note-AAAS-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> From 1966 onwards, Robbins was Dean of the School of Medicine at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Case_Western_Reserve_University_School_of_Medicine\" title=\"Case Western Reserve University School of Medicine\">Case Western<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Frederick_C._Robbins#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He led the medical school until 1980 when he assumed the Presidency of the National Academy of Sciences' <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Institute_of_Medicine\" title=\"Institute of Medicine\">Institute of Medicine<\/a>. Five years later, in 1985, Robbins returned to Case Western Reserve as Dean Emeritus and distinguished University professor Emeritus.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Frederick_C._Robbins#cite_note-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He continued to be a fixture at the medical school until his death in 2003. The medical school's \"Frederick C. Robbins Society\" is named in his honor.<\/p><p>Robbins received the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Benjamin_Franklin_Medal_for_Distinguished_Achievement_in_the_Sciences\" title=\"Benjamin Franklin Medal for Distinguished Achievement in the Sciences\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Benjamin Franklin Medal for Distinguished Achievement in the Sciences<\/a> of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/American_Philosophical_Society\" title=\"American Philosophical Society\">American Philosophical Society<\/a> in 1999.<sup id=\"cite_ref-franklinscience_recipients_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Frederick_C._Robbins#cite_note-franklinscience_recipients-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p><br style=\"clear:both;\"><\/p>","name":"Frederick C. Robbins","place_of_birth":"Auburn, Alabama","place_of_death":"Cleveland ,  Ohio","text":"Frederick C. Robbins , Physiology or Medicine, 1954","year":1954.0}